Name: ControlState
Remarks: Contains the code identifies the current state of the equipment.  When reported related to a control state transition, its value should represent the state current after the transition.

Name: PreviousControlState
Remarks: Contains the code describing previous control state of the equipment, before the most recent control state change.

Name: LimitsEnabled
Remarks: VID of the object to be limit-monitored.

Name: SMPn
Remarks: The current sampling count based on the trace n.

Name: TOTSMPn
Remarks: The total sampling count from the start to the end, based on the trace n.

Name: TRIDn
Remarks: ID of the old trace n.

Name: SpoolCountActual
Remarks: Count of the messages actually contained in the equipment’s spool area.

Name: SpoolCountTotal
Remarks: Count of the total number of primary messages directed to the spool.

Name: SpoolEnabled
Remarks: The current state indicating whether the spool has been performed or not.

Remarks: The timestamp from the time spooling last became active.

Name: SpoolFullTime

Name: SpoolLoadSubstate

Name: AlarmsEnabled
Remarks: Contains the list of alarms (ALIDs) enabled for reporting (via Stream 5).

Name: AlarmsSet
Remarks: Content of this variable is a list of alarms (ALIDs) currently in the UNSAFE (alarm set) state, regardless whether the alarms are enabled for reporting.

Name: EventsEnabled
Remarks: Contains the event list (CEID) valid for reporting (via Stream 6).

Name: Clock
Remarks: The current value of the equipment’s internal clock.

Name: ProcessState
Remarks: Contains the code that identifies the current processing state of the equipment.  When reported related to a processing state transition, its value represents the state current after the transition.

Name: PreviousProcessState
Remarks: The previous processing state of the equipment, before the most recent process state change.
Contents of the data are same as ProcessState.

Name: RCnPMMaintenanceState
Remarks: PM maintenance information of reactor n.
If the deposition count exceeds the deposition count limit, the reactor becomes PM maintenance mode.
At the PM maintenance state, if the deposition count is set below the deposition count limit, PM maintenance state is released.
If the wafer count exceeds the wafer count limit, the WHC becomes TM maintenance mode.
At the TM maintenance state, if the wafer count is set below the wafer count limit, TM maintenance state is released.
